<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1821,2028]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1436,151,501]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,1893,1919]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Recognition.</emphasis>
Small greyish delicate flies (body length 
<quantity box="[809,922,1893,1920]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.25" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" unit="mm" value="3.25" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="3.0">3–3.5 mm</quantity>
) with very slender legs almost lacking distinct setae, eyes dichoptic in both sexes, separated by broad V-shaped flattened frons; legs black to reddish brown, “knees” often somewhat paler; habitually very similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Melander" baseAuthorityYear="1902" box="[818,935,1965,1992]" class="Insecta" family="Brachystomatidae" genus="Heleodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pullata">
<emphasis box="[818,838,1966,1991]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[856,935,1965,1991]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">pullata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[954,1026,1965,1991]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–5" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1640,1664]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,183,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-20@8.[151,1437,181,1616]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 2–5. Brachystomatidae (2) and Empididae, Clinocerinae (3–5). 2. Heleodromia pullata (Melander), male habitus, lateral view; 3. Clinocera nivalis (Zetterstedt), male habitus, lateral view; 4. Trichoclinocera lapponica (Ringdahl), male habitus, lateral view; 5. same species, male postabdomen, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406991/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
, see below). Male terminalia large, reniform; tergite 8 not broader than sternite 8, only produced medially as a shallow bilobed to forked projection and lacking posterolateral projection (
<bibRefCitation author="Sinclair, B. J. &amp; Brooks, S. E. &amp; Cumming, J. M. &amp; Coovert, G. A." box="[576,850,151,177]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="629 - 651" refId="ref65374" refString="Sinclair, B. J., Brooks, S. E., Cumming, J. M. &amp; Coovert, G. A. (2011) Revision of the Nearctic species of Heleodromia (Diptera: Empidoidea: Brachystomatidae). The Canadian Entomologist, 143, 629 - 651. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / n 11 - 036" type="journal article" year="2011">
Sinclair 
<emphasis box="[672,722,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
. 2011: 641
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 10); epandrial lobe slender, finger-like, bearing apical seta; surstylus slender, finger-like, with scattered setae, with small preapical thumb-like projection medially; apex with short dentiform process; phallus with slender, needle-like apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,501]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,258,284]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Distribution.</emphasis>
Holarctic. The distribution of this species appears to be represented by widely disjunct populations exhibiting boreo-alpine connections in Europe and North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Plant, A." box="[929,1057,294,321]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="263" refId="ref64561" refString="Plant, A. (2005) Heleodromia irwini Wagner (Diptera: Empididae), an English boreo-alpine relict? British Journal of Entomology and Natural History, 18, 263." type="journal article" year="2005">Plant 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Plant, A. R. &amp; Jonassen, T. &amp; Grootaert, P. &amp; Meyer, H. &amp; Pollet, M. &amp; Drake, M." box="[1071,1266,295,321]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="852 - 868" refId="ref64594" refString="Plant, A. R., Jonassen, T., Grootaert, P., Meyer, H., Pollet, M. &amp; Drake, M. (2017) The arrow points north-endemic areas and post-Devensian assembly of the British Empidoidea fauna (Insecta: Diptera). Biological Journal of the Linnean Society, 120, 852 - 868. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / biolinnean / blw 011" type="journal article" year="2017">
Plant 
<emphasis box="[1139,1191,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Sinclair, B. J. &amp; Brooks, S. E. &amp; Cumming, J. M. &amp; Coovert, G. A." pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="629 - 651" refId="ref65374" refString="Sinclair, B. J., Brooks, S. E., Cumming, J. M. &amp; Coovert, G. A. (2011) Revision of the Nearctic species of Heleodromia (Diptera: Empidoidea: Brachystomatidae). The Canadian Entomologist, 143, 629 - 651. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / n 11 - 036" type="journal article" year="2011">
Sinclair 
<emphasis box="[1377,1429,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
. 2011
</bibRefCitation>
). Our record of 
<taxonomicName box="[391,492,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Brachystomatidae" genus="Heleodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="irwini">
<emphasis box="[391,411,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[425,492,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">irwini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Wrangel Island may support this suggestion. In Eurasia, this species is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[214,299,367,393]" name="Austria" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Austria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[313,418,367,393]" name="Germany" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Germany</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[431,483,367,393]" name="Italy" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Italy</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[497,634,367,393]" name="Switzerland" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[648,746,367,393]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Scotland</collectingCountry>
and the Far East of 
<collectingCountry box="[986,1061,367,393]" name="Russia" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Russia</collectingCountry>
(Amurskaya and Magadanskaya Provinces); in North America, it is recorded from western part of 
<collectingCountry box="[882,966,403,429]" name="Canada" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Canada</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1020,1080,403,429]" name="United States of America" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">USA</collectingCountry>
. It seems that 
<taxonomicName box="[1238,1339,403,428]" class="Insecta" family="Brachystomatidae" genus="Heleodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="irwini">
<emphasis box="[1238,1339,403,428]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">H. irwini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found here for the first time from the tundra zone.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,501]" box="[199,919,474,501]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,474,500]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Habitat.</emphasis>
The species was collected in wetlands in a river valley.
</paragraph>
